Need for Speed: The Run is a race across America.
Rese<0xC3><0xB1>a
A trip, in principle carefree, is complicated due to a series of improper neglects of a routine trip during tomorrow’s shift.
To a certain extent, expectations were met, but that was of no use, if, in fact, nothing extraordinary was intended to be done.
The new installment, to which the title is added The Run, aroused high expectations already before its premiere.
It promised to give new airs to the old Need for Speed racing saga and, after all, it appears as a game that should not end up being again a genre of action without more.
We are also curious to know what the inserted scenes would look like, where the main character gets out of the car and walks on his own foot.
As is usually the case in the NFS series, the results don’t vary much from what we expected.
There are races that can be considered acceptable, but in the total count points are lost due to absurd failures, which have been appearing in the series for years.
In reality they cannot even be called mistakes, but rather it is the incomprehensible ruse of programmers.
The adventure begins very well.
You are introduced to a story whose protagonist, Jack, has certain personal problems; to solve them, he is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You sit behind the wheel on the west coast, in San Francisco, and your mission is to get to New York first.
The idea is to offer something interesting.
The route is divided into ten stages and then into more than fifty races.
It follows that each race takes place on a different route and the stages are located in different environments, which are quite diverse and interesting.
Thus, one does not even remotely have the feeling that the game always offers the same.
Some of the environments are even pleasing to the eye, although the technical level of the graph is equivalent to that of previous deliveries of the series.
Therefore, it is nothing from the other world.
But the walk through the desert, the autumn landscape or the high mountains covered with snow produce a very pleasant visual effect.
In addition, races are diversified from time to time by an atypical element.
So, for example, in the desert you find a sandstorm that decreases visibility.
In the mountains, you have to be careful not to bury an avalanche.
According to that, each of the races is very well developed.
There are only a couple of models, but that’s enough.
For a moment, you try to get ahead of a required number of rivals (normal in a classic race), then you try to win time (timed classic duel) and then a duel awaits you against a single opponent.
In the midst of all this sometimes the police appear, which only makes things even more difficult.
The novelty is the landscapes outside the car.
Interactive animations are presented when Jack, in most cases, has to escape from someone and you have to help him, always pressing the right button at the right time.
Nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that there are far fewer landscapes in the game than you might expect (in particular, there are only three).
But the end result is positive, because this element does not become annoying and, in the context already mentioned, is one of the elements that make the game more interesting.
The driving model follows in the footsteps of previous episodes.
That means that today it is no longer a big deal, but it cannot be said to be bad.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you can look elsewhere.
But to a race conceived with enough action this style of driving is quite suitable, although we can find something better among the games of the competition.
So far, everything in order.
But problems arise after a certain time.
Unlike the correct driving models, the same is no longer the case with collisions.
Games like this can not be expected to recreate complicated deformations and collisions, but in fact before a blow against any object, you can not predict how your car will react, with which everything is not in order.
It is typical that, when making a very tight overtaking or circulating the car with normal traffic, there are only slight frictions, but in other almost identical situations, your car ends up making uncontrolled wheelbarrows.
Or even completely destroyed.
Thanks to the reset system, there are no major problems, but it can put you in a bad mood.
The resets are scheduled in such a way that when you have an accident or get off the track, the game returns you to the last rescue point on the track.
However, in each race only five resets are available.
If you consume all of them, you have to restart the race from the beginning.
So it's nothing more than a help in case something goes wrong, but it's not very reliable.
Sometimes, not even resetting helps, it only helps to learn the given stage of memory.
A big disadvantage of the game is that the same facts are repeated in different places.
In some curves, for example, you have to enter in a specific way; otherwise, they are impossible to take.
Other times you find yourself somewhere "civil" vehicles always with the same configuration, even if you are the first, fifth or arrived five minutes before or after.
This makes you angry especially in situations, when you see that two cars that go to meet in opposite directions, your opponent advances without problems, but when you arrive, you must turn or brake.
It doesn’t matter when you arrive, because it’s programmed because the “surprise” will always happen in front of your noses.
Opponents also have an advantage.
Throughout the game you will reach places where, regardless of the moment, you will always be ahead of the same opponent in the same place.
In addition, this happens at the end of the game, on a long bridge, which is even more shocking.
Your opponent must arrive before you, at any price.
When it is in front of you, it makes it difficult for you to see the cars coming from the front, so at the beginning you can make the car papilla.
You can understand the idea of creating a game with maximum doses of suspense and adrenaline, but the execution is so apparent that it will surely disappoint you right away.
And it’s a shame, because although the model of the trip is simple, the game is fun and action-packed, so it’s often not possible to follow in detail what happens or where.
And it really doesn’t matter, whether the merit takes the idea with fifty exclusive tracks or qualifying in the race so it doesn’t beat the boredom, or anything else.
An unusual idea is to change cars during races.
You have to pay attention to the gasoline suppliers next to the road, because that is where you have to change cars, although in the vast majority of cases you will have enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
Sports cars are suitable for urban areas, American strong cars for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical driving, for example, on mountain roads with curves.
In addition to the main narrative thread also appears a thread of parallel challenges, that is, there are races in specific places that you will know by the stories.
Here you will get not only medals, but also experience points for your profile, which serves both the challenges and the stories.
Upon reaching the top level, the driver opens up several possibilities, starting with the car and ending with funds for the profile.
At the same time, an Autolog online feature is connected, which compares your results with those of other players and provides other community features.
One of the most difficult elements to understand is how the last race in history is made.
By car you get to the subway tunnel (pass), where you start to run in the dark along the tracks (pass).
The speedometer marks you between 150 and 200 km/h (pass) and, suddenly, the subway convoy arrives behind you and takes you straight ahead.
In the newsroom we will surely have a discussion about this for several days, about whether during the programming of the game no one thought even a little or if the authors really take us for a panda of fools.
The technical part of the game is nothing extraordinary, but at least the overall visual effects result in most pleasant cases, sometimes even superb.
Well, what a pity that, in the most tense moments, the image quality is reduced and, sometimes, in a serious way.
This mainly affects accidents where many participants are involved, when continuous image quality is no longer valid.
The audio is fine and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In order to be liked by most of the youth group, the soundtrack belongs to the category "each of his father and mother", but it can be assumed that no one would buy the game just for his music.
The final feel of Need for Speed: The Run is rather confusing.
If the game avoided absolutely stupid mistakes, we would have trouble asserting that The Run is the best NFS game of recent years.
It gives the feeling that the game is not finished.
The fun is assured, but be prepared because mistakes will hit you in the eyes with the force of airport reflectors.
