Brand story:
The innovative IBM begins its second century of existence
If someone were to search for a term that would very accurately define IBM’s strategy, the most approximate would be “long term.”
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet it has already been a hundred years since its foundation.
The basis of this long-term character was laid by the first head of the firm, the visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the motto that many problems in the world have a solution if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became his label, around which the life of the giant future will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began publishing in 1935).
Watson was also the basis of a carefully raised corporate culture.
“For us, IBM implies a long-term thinking, a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM has survived and prospered for a hundred years for that reason, because it remained true to its basic principles, but without fear of the changes around it.
That has allowed us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We look forward to further prosperity in our second century,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company’s current director.
A sophisticated system
Watson, as early as the 1930s, cared for his employees as the entrepreneur of Bata in the Czech Republic (IBM employees were among the first American operators to enjoy paid vacations, insurance, stylish uniforms, and a sophisticated pay system that rewarded top inventors and sellers.
The same long-term sophistication keeps IBM in the relationship with the customer.
From the very beginning the company knew how to discover talents (being one of the first companies in the world to end any kind of discrimination, I could choose without problems).
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy is the current plan of IBM, with which Palmisano will be replaced next year by a woman: Virginia Rometty.
She has been working at IBM for thirty years, where she has been head of sales, marketing and strategies.
In recent years, IBM has participated in the so-called virtual meetings, a rain of online ideas, from which a myriad of future strategies and innovations arise.
It is not surprising that there are ideas, since almost half a million people work at the firm.
An institution with a good reputation
The fixed position in the business provides the company with a strong internal and external image.
“From the outset, IBM has maintained an institution rather than a technology company,” says Harvard Business School economist and author of the book on IBM, Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company trying to solve business problems for technology users,” said George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says, there is a difference between entering the business and creating a business directly.
IBM - or the "Great Green" - as it is known in the U.S. familiarly because of its logo, has become one of the largest companies in the world in the last hundred years.
It is possibly the most versatile technology company (develops both computers and programs, infrastructures and web hosting services within a wide range of services, ranging from servers to nanotechnology).
It holds the largest number of patents from all U.S. technology companies and five of its employees have received the Nobel Prize.
His inventions include ATMs, payment cards, financial exchanges, barcodes and floppy disks.
IBM has become the second-largest technology firm by market capitalization (the first is Apple), when it first surpassed Microsoft in 1996.
Looking to the future
Not all products and innovations have just satisfied the taste of customers and the moment (IBM did not bet on its own operating system, OS/2, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers).
“If your business is based on progress, you cannot emotionally anchor yourself in the past,” Samuel J. Palmisano said.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its bases on other platforms (and likewise, if they don’t work, abandons them).
And this is the difference from the competition, Microsoft, which basically stays and always falls exclusively with Windows.
Technology of the future
In terms of sales, IBM is primarily engaged in services, of which approximately one-fifth is programmed and one-fifth is equipment.
However, even in 1990 the equipment accounted for more than half of the share of suppliers.
As of 2000, IBM has sold low-yield assets for a total value of $15 billion. During the same period, it has invested $58 billion in the purchase of future technology.
Investments have continued since 2008, when the modern global financial crisis first manifested itself.
IBM is acting on the premises of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who during the Great Economic Crisis of 29 increased investments.
It seems that until now the company IBM has managed to cope with the crisis.
The value of IBM shares since the beginning of 2008 has increased stratospherically to 120%, the company's net profit has not stopped increasing.
IBM’s currency is to change everything except its value.
One can therefore expect that when the next crisis comes, this flexible giant will endure.
IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Space Flight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, its original name being Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 - it was originally a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation that gave rise to IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He possessed inventions such as the famous "ticking clock", which allows to control the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was the businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint hired the head of a competing company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him with the management of the company.
The new leader eclipsed IBM’s founder (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are based).
Watson led the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During the first four years that Watson led the company, revenue doubled by $9 million and began the company’s great expansion across the continents.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after nearly forty years in the chair of the boss, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM personnel and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
In 1964, IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which introduced the computer standard of the time, came on the market under the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, in turn, acquired the consulting part of Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began offering comprehensive, high-value-added consulting and services.
The strategy that IBM has paid for over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept, i.e., “a smarter planet.”
Its aim is to make more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned and circumstances have not improved, for example in terms of transport and city management.
For the retail sector, IBM recently unveiled the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the full business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
Already in 1932 it opened a branch in Czechoslovakia at the time, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe is located in Prague. Also here there is a world-renowned research team that works with voice recognition.
