BAsD urges Asia to help rescue eurozone
The Asian Development Bank (ADB) has called on India and China to prepare to help rescue the eurozone from its sovereign debt crisis to avert a long-term recession that would impede the growth of Asian economies.
Rajat Nag, director general of the Manila-based Asian Development Bank, said the world’s two fastest-growing major economies had to “do everything possible” to accelerate the economic bloc’s recovery either through the International Monetary Fund or directly through bilateral agreements.
He warned against the BRIC [Brazil, Russia, India, China] countries observing Europe’s difficulties in an “unbiased” way and said that Asia’s financial assistance along with European leadership and resources would help avert a long-term crisis in the global economy.
"We're all in this together."
“So anyone who can help Europe out of the crisis is useful,” he told the Financial Times in an interview at the World Economic Forum in Mumbai.
“Asia may be protected to some extent, but it cannot be immune.”
"So if China and India can help, let it be by all means."
The European monetary union has been severely undermined by a sovereign debt crisis in recent months.
In recent days, Italy’s borrowing costs have skyrocketed dangerously and the prime ministers of Italy and Greece have resigned.
The current sovereign debt crisis in Europe has heightened fears that it could push the global economy into recession and has generated calls for major emerging economies to come together to help the eurozone find a solution.
Mr Nag predicted that any support from Asia would be channelled through the IMF, but said that bilateral assistance – such as the purchase of bonds from the EU bailout fund, the European Financial Stability Fund – offered greater bargaining power for Europe’s Asian partners.
Anand Sharma, India’s trade minister, said that “India will do everything possible” to help the eurozone as its own economy was now suffering from falling exports and depletion of foreign capital inflows.
“Nobody wants the eurozone to remain unstable and turbulent,” he said.
“We have monumental challenges and we have to maintain a high level of growth.”
“It’s not an option, it’s an imperative, because where do we find employment for tens of millions of our young men and women?”
Others argue that developing economies like India have no responsibility to help wealthy Europeans when they face their own deep economic problems.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the U.S., said it would be politically very difficult to sell aid to Europe for India’s 1 billion two hundred thousand people, of whom as many as 800 million live on about $2 a day or less.
"At some point they will realize that the Greeks are retiring at the age of 50 and going on vacation to the beaches and that will not fall well," he said.
Lee Howell, managing director of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India’s reserves should be used to keep the numerous and well-paid workers in the Greek public sector, in jobs from mismanaged companies, and generating losses such as railways.
Mr Nag said the eurozone crisis threatens "important chain effects" across Asia.
The Asian Development Bank’s forecast of 7.5 percent economic growth in Asia for 2011/12 is now facing “downside risks” due to Europe’s threat.
He said vulnerable emerging markets needed to make “contingency plans” to protect themselves from a crisis and significant capital outflows from their economies.
Pentagon's Serious Warnings About Possible Defense Cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta warmed Congress on Monday, warning that impending automatic budget cuts could undermine national security and provoke a financial chain reaction from the Pentagon’s corridors to Afghanistan’s battlefields to civilian assembly lines.
The Pentagon is already digesting $450 billion in cuts over the next decade, but now fears an additional $600 billion or more in cuts that may be imminent if Congress fails to agree on spending.
"The impact of these cuts would be devastating for the department," Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, Republican for Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, Republican for South Carolina.
He said that the failure of Congress to reach an agreement on the budget and its consequence, the so-called "kidnapping", would result in 23 percent global reductions and a halt to many new projects.
“Such a large cut, applied in this indiscriminate way, would make most of our naval and construction projects impossible to execute – you can’t buy three-quarters of a ship or a building – and seriously damage other modernization efforts,” Panetta wrote to senators.
“We would also be forced to involuntarily detach many of our civilian officials and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, it is almost certain that we would have to license civilians in order to meet the target.”
“These changes would break faith with those who maintain our army and would seriously damage goodwill.”
Cuts over time would reach combat troops, Panetta said.
“While funding for wartime accounts in the Overseas Contingency Operations accounts is not directly affected by the kidnapping, war efforts would be negatively affected by serious disruptions to basic budgets,” Panetta warned.
“The recruitment of personnel would be reduced, which would lead to delays in contracts and supervision of the contract that supports the war.”
“The payroll staff would be reduced, resulting in delays in payments to wartime suppliers, and legal and political support would be interrupted.”
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days ago, asking for information on the possible impact of automatic cuts on the Department of Defense.
“The consequence of a kidnapping in the Department of Defense would cause a rapid decline of the United States as the world’s leading military power.”
"We strongly oppose this draconian action," the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they published Panetta's letter.
“This is not a result that one can live with, and certainly not one that we should impose on ourselves.”
“The kidnapping is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it should not be allowed to happen.”
Whether Panetta’s letter and recent warnings from senators will increase pressure for a budget commitment or intensify calls to exempt the Pentagon from cuts is yet to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly outspoken about possible cuts, even though she came to a job at the top of the Pentagon with years of budgeting experience in Congress and the White House and knowing she was facing difficult decisions.
At a news conference last week, the Secretary of Defense painted a grim picture of what could be ahead – an army with a shell, but not a core.
"It's a ship without sailors."
"It's a bullet-free brigade."
"It's an aerial wing without enough trained pilots."
“It’s a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs without enough trained soldiers to carry out the mission,” Panetta said in his opening words at the Pentagon.
"It is a force that suffers from low morale, poor preparation and is not able to keep up with potential adversaries."
"Indeed, it invites aggression..."
In an appendix to her letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta outlines new details of how reductions “generate significant operational risks: delays in crisis, conflict and disaster response time; severely limits our ability to be deployed and previously engaged around the world; and poses an unacceptable risk in future combat operations.”
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could face the axe, including those already being tested and some only in the early stages of planning.
This list includes the F35 Joint Strike Fighter fighter aircraft, a planned new bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new coastal combat ship and the new ground combat vehicle that the Army and Navy need to replace, the humvee.
Stopping further development and testing of the F35 could generate about $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but its proponents say it is the next vital step in improving and tackling potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to Detect a Lie
A look at the most recent headlines shows us how serious and ubiquitous deception and lies are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging allegations of sexual harassment with several women; each side accuses of lying to the other.
Administrators at Pennsylvania State University have been charged with perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was "pilled" with an open microphone claiming to U.S. President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed careers and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner ridiculed his denials quickly refuted by the irrefutable proof.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And again, no one who lives it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton while lying during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been instances where teachers have given exam responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching the opposite are sending the message that lying and deceiving are acceptable.
How much deception do we find ourselves?
On any given day, studies show that they can lie to you anywhere from 10 to 200 times.
That’s for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times in the first 10 minutes of meeting each other.
Detecting lies, or “locating lies,” is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, for example, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim: “I have you”, the detection of deception is a branch of serious knowledge based on scientific data obtained during the last six decades at prestigious universities that conducted in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lies have been refuted.
The liars look in the eyes.
They don’t always stutter, bark, blush or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can get to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation, and timing.
I spent several years surveying scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read others well, make them feel comfortable, manage their own emotions and intuitively feel how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more “self-oriented lies,” while women tell more “other-oriented” lies—usually to protect someone’s feelings—that married people lie less often to their partners than people who are not married (but they tend to be afraid to lie).
We also know that if you are perceived as a villain, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the subject’s usual behavior.
This is called "creating a baseline".
It helps to provide benchmarks for later measurement of changes.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter and vocal characteristic.
It’s best to know if someone normally taps their foot all the time so as not to make unfair accusations when they see their feet tapping in the middle of the meeting.
Then look for deceptive, verbal and non-verbal behavior groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as alarm signals, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze their upper body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a “post-interview mood swing” — that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
Often interrogators falsely suggest that the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
It also pays attention to the subject's vocabulary.
Scott Peterson put his foot to the bottom and used the time spent while claiming that his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: “I didn’t have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell the truth... to what I know... to my understanding."
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a warning sign.
There is no magic formula to detect lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve anyone’s chances of avoiding being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
Controversial pipeline plan diverted after U.S. threat of delay in approval
Days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a planned pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico -- infuriating unions, while appeasing environmentalists -- the company seeking to build the pipeline says it is willing to redirect the project to reroute it.
TransCanada said Monday night it will move the planned pipeline out of the environmentally sensitive Sandhills area in Nebraska, and it is confident the project will win approval.
The company announced the decision at a news conference at the Nebraska Capitol.
TransCanada CEO Alex Pourbax says the company maintains its confidence that over time the pipeline will be approved, although it is true that it will take a different route.
This comes after the State Department announced last week that it would delay the decision for a federal permit for the project until new potential routes to avoid the areas of Nebraska’s Sandhills and the Ogallala Aquifer, a vast groundwater supply, are studied.
