Italy’s appointed prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet with Italy’s president on Wednesday to present the new government facing a crisis that has put Italy on the brink of economic disaster and endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
He is expected to present a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he will present to the president the outcome of his talks with political parties in his attempt to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," he told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he could form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles have been overcome.
The “framework is now well outlined,” he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, far less than normal, while Italy is battling a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration, led by former European Commissioner Monti, must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders in order to regain shattered confidence in Italy.
Stressing pressure on Monti to hurry, the volatility of the markets put the yield on Italian BTP bonds at 10 years above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be bailed out.
Emma Marcegaglia, head of Italian employer Confindustria, told the press after meeting with Monti: "We said we would be very supportive of this government."
We believe that this government is the last chance for Italy to get out of this emergency situation.
Monti’s chances of success were boosted considerably by the support of Silvio Berlusconi’s PDL party, whom the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is significant because so far many of its members have opposed the technocratic majority government that is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
The new Monti government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockade or delay in their efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on the financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks joined the pressure by warning that a failure of Monti would be a disaster.
On Monday, Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as with youth and women’s organizations.
It will end its round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief pause at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would resign, the costs of the Italian debt have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty about whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Rescue Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the eurozone’s current financial defenses.
Monti has said his government should last until the next election, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before the election.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but major parties insist it should consist only of technicians, an indication of his concerns over a process forced by financial pressure.
