MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security conducts research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people; it is supported by NPI specialists
The Mexican Social Security Institute (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to discover the obesity gene in children and adolescents, called the “Genetics of Childhood and Adolescent Obesity” protocol, which will allow markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital de Especialidades of the National Medical Center Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
The research invites to participate the population, whether or not they have the right, to go to the participating IMSS sports units in the Valley of Mexico, where the tests for minors are carried out, every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He pointed out that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (State of Western Mexico) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualc<0xC3><0xB3>yolt Sports Unit (State of Eastern Mexico).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Independence Sports Unit (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Morelos Sports Unit (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in children and young Mexicans to prevent the onset of chronic degenerative diseases.
On 14 November, World Diabetes Day, he said that the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14 years old, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the implementation of specific food questionnaires.
They will also be asked about physical activity and hereditary disease history, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, size, waist circumference), blood pressure measurement, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (genes associated with childhood obesity are sought to be identified) are applied to all participants.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez noted that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in children.
"The 1999 and 2006 health surveys indicated that in just six years there was a 77 percent increase in obesity in the case of boys, and 47 percent in the case of girls; in terms of overweight, a dramatic increase was also observed," the IMSS specialist noted.
He indicated that the justification for searching for the markers lies in the fact that the country’s population differs from others in its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian heritage, 30 percent European and five percent African and this condition is reflected in the genes that are associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calories) and that it is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive assessment of the children, which allows detecting if they have some degree of overweight or obesity.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) in the neck and forearm, indicating the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors deliver it in writing to parents, who are explained each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent diseases.
Cruz L<0xC3><0xB3>pez explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary, which is the lack of daily physical activity, staying most of the day sitting in front of the TV and using means of transportation instead of walking short distances.
It is also due to the high calorie intake, i.e. the higher consumption of sugary drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, hamburger, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetics that are analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM asphalt would avoid bumps
Rafael Herrera, a researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops polymer-modified asphalts to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals sent by the pavement were met, it would not be necessary to repair about 200,000 bumps each rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of the Valley of Mexico, warned Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who could even reduce the number, if the process of construction and maintenance of the pavement is necessary.
In his conference A Technological Opinion of the Baches, dictated in the framework of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory in charge of developing modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with characteristics similar to those of the asphalt, but with greater mechanical strength, both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera estimated that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the weather is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve their performance and, therefore, the formation of bumps.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, some of which are high molecular weight, called asphalts, and others of low molecular weight, called maltenes, which together give the pavement its characteristic viscoelastic behavior.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists in that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it behaves like a liquid, at 120 degrees centigrade its viscosity is very high and at 50 degrees centigrade it presents an almost solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, he added.
This means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not uniform, but it is modified during the day according to environmental and temperature conditions, the specialist in chemical engineering warned.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City are mostly covered by flexible pavement, which consists of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the most superficial layers is the asphalt folder, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and then compacted.
Each of the stones that constitute the folder, he pointed out, is bathed in asphalt.
As vehicles pass through and efforts are generated, this allows the forces to spread very well on the pavement.
If it were modified asphalt, it would spread even better, the chemical engineer said.
Over the asphalt folder, abounded, is placed a last layer called rolling folder, which is made of a fine stone material, that is, a sand that is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer that is going to be in contact with the rims of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt folder and provide friction on the road.
Being the part of the pavement that will receive and spread the efforts, the rolling folder also requires to have the proper thickness and the material from which it is made must be taken care of.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, are also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he said, because it significantly affects the performance of the asphalt folder.
When the soil gets wet, the water diffuses inside the folder and it is difficult for it to come out, this causes softening of all layers of the floor and, therefore, the formation of bumps.
In the process of forming a bump, he said, the first to wear out is the bearing film and only then the asphalt folder is affected, but the damage does not occur instantly, but is a process that should be attended to at first signals with proper maintenance programs.
The member of the National System of Researchers also explained that the vehicle load is another important factor in the formation of bumps and, therefore, the thickness of each of the layers of the pavement must always be in relation to the vehicle load and ensure that it is fulfilled, to prevent the formation of bumps frequently.
Rafael Herrera warned that there is still a lot to research and work on asphalt, for example, asphalt emulsions, which in other countries are already even on the market and allow you to repair the bumps with ease and without the need to use high temperatures.
