Since last March, the Japanese economy has been paralyzed, still recovering from the devastating earthquake that turned into a nuclear crisis, the worst catastrophe the country has suffered since World War II.
The first estimates of the Tokyo Government amounted to $300 billion in material losses, a blow that, despite the difficult global context, appears to have subsided.
After three consecutive quarters of declines, the Gross Domestic Product (GDP) data between July and September was definitely a turning point: GDP increased by 1.5% compared to the previous quarter and by 6% at the annualized rate.
The record in the second quarter - for the Japanese, the fiscal year begins in March 2012 - also represents the highest rate of growth since the period from January to March 2010.
The recovery is partly explained by the resurgence of the purchase of machinery to restore areas devastated by the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
In fact, companies increased their investments by 1.1%, compared with a 0.9% decline in capital expenditures from January to March, the first regression after six months of uninterrupted increases.
However, the real revulsion of the Japanese economy is not solely based on the Keynesian impulse that invites us to take advantage of crises to reinforce – or rebuild – infrastructure, to use the shortfalls to grow from scratch.
Japan has awakened, above all, thanks to the evolution of domestic consumption, which currently accounts for 60% of Japan's GDP.
This variable climbed by 1%, driven by increased spending on vehicles, travel and leisure activities.
