Tokyo has been entrusted to the domestic market, when the yen - the Japanese currency - has become one of the "refugee values" chosen by investors fleeing the euro zone debt crisis and the turbulent US forecasts, a privilege that weighs like a slab on the accounts of exporting companies.
With a stronger currency, products are more expensive abroad, a serious setback for a country whose line of economic floatation is determined by the health of large technology groups.
Toyota or Sony, for example, lumped their weak results between July and September to the yen.
While markets continue their siege of the EU’s peripheral countries, Yoshihiko Noda’s government does not lower its guard.
“We need to be aware of the risks that persist, such as the deterioration of some foreign economies, the impact of Thailand’s floods and the rapid appreciation of the yen,” said Secretary of State for Economic Policy Motohisa Furukawa.
