Energy policy:
Facts are worth more than dogmas.
If there’s one issue that can’t be addressed with short-term considerations or just thinking about emotions, it’s energy policy.
The availability and cost of electricity directly influence the purchasing power and competitiveness of companies.
It is appropriate that an electoral meeting be the time to reflect on such issues and on the place of nuclear energy.
The debate will only be useful if it examines the overall economic, social and environmental consequences of the proposed options.
The French must base their opinion on objective facts, on rational data.
Now that we are 7 billion people on the planet, demographic evolution will double electricity demand by 2050, unless a huge portion of the world’s population is deprived of a vital element.
At the same time, the growing scarcity of fossil resources must be alleviated to continue producing electricity continuously, not forgetting the urgent need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions to fight climate change, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
That is why Germany remains alone in its decision to give up nuclear energy.
That is not the case either for Belgium, which submits its own to the need to find a source capable of replacing it, or for Switzerland, which aims only to build state-of-the-art power plants.
On the other hand, Great Britain, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name a few examples, are moving forward with determination with their projects.
The United States, for its part, after Fukushima decided to add a unit to its park, resuming the construction of a power plant interrupted after the Three Mile Island accident.
If the German model, based on renewable energies, is sometimes presented as an example, reality goes against such discourse.
The Berlin election will mean an increase in the price of electricity, an increased energy dependence due to the increased need for imported gas, in particular from Russia, an increase in CO2 emissions from the construction of gas and coal plants.
In a few months, the harmful effects will be noticed.
The case of Denmark must be considered.
European champion in the wind sector, of which 30% of its electricity is obtained, is also one of the major users of coal and gas due to the intermittency of the wind; for this reason, its CO2 emissions and the price of its electricity are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the European average.
On the contrary, thanks to the constancy of our energy policy, our neighbors pay an electricity bill 40% higher than that of French households.
While in a globalized economy the cost of energy is a key factor in competitiveness and a guarantee of the maintenance of industrial utility in the national territory, French companies benefit from the cheapest electricity in Europe.
For that reason, any significant reduction in nuclear power would mean a sharp rise in the price of electricity, which would detract from the wonderful statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defense of our purchasing power.
This is a price that the vast majority of French people refuse to pay and, in fact, do not in principle oppose this type of energy, as surveys show.
Let us remember that the energy policy of our country has lost to build an industrial sector with 125,000 managerial jobs and 410,000 indirect jobs.
Widely export-oriented, it encompasses a galaxy of SMEs specialized in international markets that can create non-localizable jobs.
If France decides to abandon nuclear power, it would mean sacrificing much of those SMEs and losing <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>6 billion a year in French exports of nuclear equipment and services.
What electrician would order an EPR designed to run for sixty years, when the collapse of its manufacturer is planned?
To solve the nuclear energy equation, one must admit that there is no miraculous source of electricity production, just as there is no diabolical source.
Areva’s development of low-carbon, nuclear and renewable solutions demonstrates the complementary nature of energy sources.
In the case of nuclear energy, it is essential to maintain the highest level of safety.
In France, we have a security authority that exercises strict and transparent control over both the existing plants and the construction of Flamanville.
Our teams, of renowned professionalism, are also obsessed with safety.
In half a century, the nuclear sector has suffered three serious accidents.
Only one, that of Three Mile Island, occurred under normal operating conditions; it caused no consequences for people or the environment.
In Chernobyl, the accident was due to the design of the reactor and unforgivable human faults.
In Fukushima, some people seem to forget that the accident was due to two natural disasters of unprecedented scope, which resulted in the deaths of tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear sector will learn from this accident, as it did from the previous two.
Thanks to this progress and to cooperation between the safety authorities, and the French and German operators and manufacturers, the EPR presents a design capable of resisting such phenomena.
While it is being studied by all the electric players who want to build a power plant, the interruption of its construction in Flamanville would be a great gift for the competitors of Areva and EDF, since it would leave them free to take the lead in the inevitable development of the nuclear sector.
It is indispensable and legitimate to seek the best energy options for our country, but it would be irresponsible to let emotion, dogmas and partisan maneuvers dominate such an important debate for the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Immigration, a burden or an opportunity for the economy?
The immigration policy implemented by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from various points of view: the saturation of police, judicial and administrative services subject to the policy of figures, the compatibility of this policy with the self-proclaimed status of "country of human rights" of France.
More recently, it is the administrative harassment of foreign students that has jumped to the headlines, with the Interior Minister (see the Libération newspaper of 23 May) proclaiming from the past that France "does not need foreign talents, workers or waiters".
However, it is rarely analysed from an economic point of view.
The point is that, on this issue, there is quite a consensus between the left and the right.
In the case of the right, Jacques Chirac fixed the orientation by declaring in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed should not be a problem for a country with about two million immigrant workers", while on the left, the tone was set by Michel Rocard explaining that France "cannot take over all the misery of the world" in 1990.
The only difference, the degree of generosity
In 2005, both the left and the right shared the fear of the invasion of the national territory by a multitude of Polish plumbers.
On both sides, immigrants are seen as a burden on the French economy and society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity with which they act towards immigrants.
In his program, Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Hollande confines himself to including trivialities, indicating that co-development will solve the "migration problem".
This idea of immigration as a burden, a problem, may prove to be electorally profitable, but economically it is very expensive.
As economists Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron point out in a recent paper that summarizes the most recent knowledge on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 pp.), there is a broad consensus among countries on the positive impact of migration flows on growth and the economy.
Limiting immigration weakens growth and harms employment.
Fears about the impact of immigrants are based on the idea that they can replace national workers, in particular low-skilled workers, by pushing for lower wages.
But experience has shown that, in reality, immigrants are more complementary than substitutes for national workers and exercise mainly professions in sectors with a lack of employment.
Low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract national workers and the most skilled in dynamic sectors where training does not meet the demand for staff.
A positive effect on wages
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country that lacks anesthesiologists, the complementarity between nationals and immigrants causes the arrival of the latter to positively influence the salaries and employment of nationals.
In view of the above, Giovanni Peri calculated that an increase of 1% in migration flows means an increase in long-term real wages of between 0.6 and 0.9%.
And, regardless of the fact that the diversity that immigrants bring contributes to the creation of ideas and economic growth (there is a large proportion of naturalized American Nobel prizes and companies such as Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Immigrants are also net contributors to social systems, contributing an average of 1% of the total budget in European countries.
The International Labour Organization estimates, for example, that in Germany an immigrant who arrives at the age of 30 will make a net contribution (income minus expenses) of <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>150,000 to public budgets on average throughout his or her life.
At the beginning of his term, Nicolas Sarkozy wanted to go look for the missing growth points "with his teeth".
These teeth, which discouraged immigrants, had exactly the opposite effect.
Europe invented democracy, it just has to think of a European democracy
Democracy is a precious good, but it is also fragile.
The European continent should be able to remember this since, although it was invented in Athens more than two thousand years ago, throughout the twentieth century it has suffered the tragedies of World War, totalitarianism, the Holocaust, the gulag, but also Franco in Spain, Salazar in Portugal, the colonels in Greece.
Some may have believed that, for democracy to triumph definitively over its enemies, it would be sufficient to exercise the vote as directly as possible.
We know, since Napoleon "the Little One", that it was something thought out.
Universal suffrage, although a necessary condition for democracy, is not enough on its own and can even become an “instrument of oppression,” as former republican philosopher Etienne Vacherot put it.
No, democracy requires much more: a public space, a public spirit, values, an organization, a separation and control of powers, an education, Lights, economic and social solidarity, justice.
The crisis we are experiencing in Europe is an economic crisis, but it is about to become a political and democratic crisis.
The palinody of the true-false Greek referendum had, in this regard, a twofold revealing effect: it showed the need for a powerful return of the political sphere, but also the worrying feeling of its impossibility, of its incongruity.
This ambivalence must be considered in order to overcome it.
The truth is that the front lines of the democratic battle have now shifted and that, in many cases, Republican soldiers are no longer moving in the right direction.
We will not win if we demand a succession of national referendums, organized according to needs and disorderly.
A blank signature to the absolute European monarch or a vacancy in the nationalist hole: what options for the citizen!
No, we do not want to take blows of effect, but a common exercise, full of law, calm and continuous, of options and democracy, this time at European level.
There is no crisis in Greece, Italy, Spain, Portugal (in fact, we would not know where to end the list), because there is only one crisis, the crisis of Europe.
It is the whole of Europe that is under the orders of the markets and the rating agencies, it is the one who suffers from their impotence and their lack of solidarity.
It is the whole of Europe that is humiliated in the international sphere.
We are concerned about the transfer of sovereignty to Europe, but it is all of Europe that is slowly losing sovereignty and, with it, each of its nations.
The most urgent thing is for popular sovereignty to regain the helm of the European project.
Because only together will Europeans be able to reduce the burden of their debts, free themselves from the markets and prepare their future through investment.
The exit from the crisis will require decisions at European level that cannot be taken without full democratic legitimacy, unless it is to lead us to disaster.
After having fought for a long time against this proposal of the Socialists and Jacques Delors, everyone is now calling for European economic governance.
Let it be so.
But to think of it without further political and democratic integration, and without it being lived as such by citizens, would be a new madness and would lead us to a new dead end.
We must take on a new stage of European construction.
To build the Republic in France, it was necessary to “make” Republicans.
An interest-driven revolution would not be enough.
This lesson is still applicable.
We must build a more integrated Europe from an economic point of view.
It can only be achieved by building a more democratic Europe at the political level, a true European people's sovereignty.
To build Europe, let us make Europeans.
