The Nord Stream, a new gateway for Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which directly connects Western Europe with Russia through the Baltic Sea bottom, has already been put into service.
It must supply gas to meet the needs of thirty million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with great pomp.
Last Tuesday, more than 500 guests, including four Heads of State and Government, took part on the shores of the Baltic Sea, between orchestra music and a delicate buffet, in the inauguration of Nord Stream, the new gas pipeline that communicates directly, under the sea, Russia with Germany.
Symbolically, German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his Dutch counterpart, Mark Rutte, have turned together the steering wheel of the valve that controls the inflow of Russian gas into the Western European network.
With this new gas pipeline, an additional 27.5 million cubic meters of Russian gas will reach Western Europe each year through a first 1,224 km tidal tidal that connects the St. Petersburg region with the Land of Mecklenburg-Pomerania.
A second pipeline is expected to be completed by the end of 2012 that will provide a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, that is, enough to cover all French consumption.
In addition, there is already talk of the possibility of building a third tube for the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge work is in the air of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries had strongly opposed the project.
In fact, the Nord Stream will allow the supply of gas directly to Germany, avoiding the land passage by third countries (Poland and Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose some of their power: for them, it will be more difficult to influence Russia by threatening to close its access to Western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare the Nord Stream as a "new German-Soviet pact", referring to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is, if the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, supporting the Russian project, has obtained greater security of supply.
But the price is a weakening of Europe’s energy, given that the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
In just five years, Russia has been able to achieve its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the wealthy Western countries, large consumers of gas and with increasingly limited reserves.
“This pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that organically connects us,” Fillon said at the inauguration of the pipeline, demonstrating how big contracts in the gas sector are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles on the faces of Gazprom executives, numerous in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical achievement.
The submarine tube is made of steel coated with cement to protect it from the anchors of the ships.
It rests on the seabed, at an average depth of 200 m.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating back to World War II.
“It was necessary to remove or destroy a hundred of them, as a precaution,” said Jens Müller, a spokesman for Nord Stream.
It was also necessary to extreme measures for the protection of fauna and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake that weighs like 242 Eiffel towers and is not interrupted over its entire length: neither by valves nor by maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned in Sweden’s waters, but the project managers renounced it, seeing that the Swedes were not very willing to allow a Russian state-owned company to establish itself permanently at sea off its coasts.
“In the event of a breakdown, we will interrupt the passage of gas in less than a minute,” says Jens Müller.
In case of leakage, the gas from the pipeline will therefore be released into the atmosphere.
But builders consider it unlikely that a leak will occur, as they have predicted junctions that are forecast to have one leak every 100,000 years.
The state control of the gas pipeline is ensured by a submarine robot, dragged by a vessel, which performs external inspections, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas pipeline.
In the form of a puree, it enters the inside of the tube, which has a diameter of one meter, and moves with the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of travel at a speed of three meters per second, it provides accurate data on possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline has been designed to run for fifty years without any repairs needed.
The circulation of the gas is ensured simply by the pressure.
At the beginning it is 200 bars and at the exit of 100 bars.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leading company is Gazprom, which owns 51% of the shares.
It was joined by the Germans E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture, called Nord Stream, to build and operate the pipeline.
It is headquartered in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to Gazprom, for a renewable period of 25 years, the entire gas transport capacity.
“Gazprom will be paid for the total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas that is actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
The financing of the construction of the gas pipeline has been completed by 30% with the contribution of the shareholders and by 70% through bank loans.
The total cost of the work should reach 7.4 billion euros for the two tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment has reached 240 million.
But minority shareholders are confident they won’t outperform their investment, as Gazprom alone assumes the risk of spending.
The pipeline emerges from the Baltic in Lubmin, on a sandy coast planted with pine trees.
Valves, 4.5 meters high, form the gas outlet gate.
There are sensors that measure the pressure, temperature and specific characteristics of the gas on arrival, before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, the terminal receives one million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
In total capacity, it will be three million per hour and in 2012, six million.
Moleskine, a branded notebook.
Created half a century ago by an Italian company, Moleskine wants to give people back their taste for writing.
It has an air of adventure, of hours of writing in the light of a candle.
The Moleskine notebook is easily recognized, with its black rectangular pastes, its rubber, its broken white leaves, as aged by time.
However, Moleskine notebooks with the current look were born... in 1997.
The Italian company Modo Modo, based in Milan, decided at that time to launch on the market a notebook of design notes, but distinguished.
Maria Sebregondi, then the company’s consultant, was in charge of launching the new product.
The booklet is inspired by an old production technique, the mole skin, which refers to a varnished cotton that was used, among other things, to cover the benches.
This type of notebook was highly valued by writers and travelers.
"Moleskine has adapted to the current taste an old and forgotten object, an icon of the avant-garde artists until the 20th century," says Maria Sebregondi, who has since become responsible for the brand in Mode Mode Mode.
And he achieved success.
Between 2006 and 2010, sales increased by 26%, to reach a volume of 12.7 million units sold.
The confidential production of the first years, in which only 3,000 notebooks were designed, has remained far away.
Moleskine goes beyond Italian borders and exports its products to 70 countries, from France to the United States.
It is difficult to determine the buyer’s profile, since the notebook attracts both businessmen and students and professionals.
Like Moleskine, its users are cosmopolitan, open-minded and cult.
The small Italian company, which had twelve employees at the beginning, now has about 100 and, since 2008, has two offices: one in Milan and the other in New York.
He distributes his notebooks in bookstores, from the Fnac to the small shops in the city center, and has been able to impose his identity.
“We have adapted to the times and the need to write, despite the boom in emails,” explains Maria Sebregondi.
This cultural signature goes hand in hand with the development of Moleskine: recently, the brand has launched the "Detour" exhibition where architects or artists exhibit their own notebook.
In August, he also released a notebook with leopard covers, on the occasion of the Locarno Film Festival.
Taking advantage of its success and this cultural aura, Moleskine has been able to diversify its products: bags, calendars, pens, computer cases... The brand covers a wide range of supports.
A success that provokes envy: in the autumn of 2006, Modo Modo was acquired by the investment fund SG Capital Europe, now Syntegra Capital, thus writing a new page in Moleskine’s history.
Why is the unemployment rate of disabled workers still so high?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
The XV Week for the Employment of the Disabled begins today.
Despite a resolute public policy, implemented since 2005, the unemployment rate among persons with disabilities doubles the average rate: 19%, compared to 9% for the entire population.
Desensitizing?
“No,” says <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, CEO of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
“The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable.
At that time, the unemployment rate was not twice but three times higher than the average.
"However, there is still a great deal to be done."
It should be noted that disabled unemployed people continue to face numerous obstacles to accessing employment.
They are usually older: 37% are over 50 years old (average 17%).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% have not finished high school and, of the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Lastly, long-term unemployment is widespread among them: 53% for the disabled, compared to 38% on average.
That is, there are numerous issues that make it especially difficult to return to the world of work and that "constitute the quid of the problem," says Christian Grapin, CEO of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help companies hire disabled workers.
These are the objective obstacles.
In addition, there are those that are not mentioned; the mentality of people advances, but too slowly.
A study conducted in April by the association IMS-Entreprendre for la Cité noted that the directors surveyed had "a low level of knowledge about disabilities," with "excessive representation of wheelchair users, physical or intellectual disabilities."
The result: private companies with more than 20 workers are far from the goal of hiring 6% of disabled workers, a goal that was set in a 1987 law.
According to the latest available figures, which date back to 2008, they reach a ratio of 2.6%.
“We now reach around 3%,” says Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the body responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The proof: the number of establishments "subject to this contribution", as well as the amounts disbursed, have decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
"The 2005 law, which increased contributions, has generated a lot of pressure for companies," explains Pierre Blanc.
“But this improvement also reflects true awareness, particularly among large groups.”
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of companies with between 20 and 49 employees have disabled employees, compared to 82% of companies with between 100 and 199 employees.
Hazard: "A Joy"
